#tsx #controlled-channel

For more context, see [[5kzr3hwx]].

# T-SGX
T-SGX @shih2017tsgx uses Intel TSX  to prevent the OS from knowing the page fault, since TSX supresses page faults on during a transaction. The system transform the program such that (almost) all code is executed in a TSX transaction. Any page fault is treated as an attack attempt by the OS. 
Reported overheads of the system is about 50%.


# Deja Vu
@chen2017detecting uses TSX to *detect* wheter an AEX has occured during the execution of critical code. The program is instrumented to periodically measure its execution time, and if the execution time deviate too much from its expected time, an AEX is detected.

```c
while (1) {
  // update counter
  if (_xbegin() == _XBEGIN_STARTED)
  {
      int rand = random();
      for (int i =0; i < rand; i++){
        // rand cycles is performed
      }
      _xend();
  }
  else {
    interrupted += 1;
    continue;
  }
  timer += rand;
}
```

A thread is used to continuously update a global timer variable.
The program is then instrumented to uses this timer to detect attacks (e.g., if a basic block takes too long to complete and the there was an interrupt, then there is a high chance that an AEX occurred).
The counter thread uses TSX to determine whether an interrupt happened.

